1-421D-B062-95C1156ED0EB</gtr:id><gtr:title>Pluralism, Public Sphere &amp;amp; Religious Otherness in Early Twentieth-Century Argentina</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-074-27-0002</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>According to certain assertions about Latin American culture and tradition, Catholicism is supposed to be one of the quintessential characteristics of this sub-continent. Certainly, to judge by its of the prominence of ecclesiastical architecture, ever since the violent irruption of Spanish colonial power, and in its influence on hegemonic discourses in the social and political spheres (whether from conservative or progressive sectors), the Catholic church has been at the forefront of a vast range of regional processes. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>This was particularly so in the first decades of the twentieth century in Argentina and other nations. Nevertheless, far from being a hegemonic actor, Catholicism had to cope with other religious currents. This is precisely the problem to be addressed by this project.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>In other words, Judaism, Protestantism, Spiritism and Pentecostalism, among others, fought against the monopolist attempts of the church to preserve a religious and political leadership in what Church leaders envisioned as a sort of Catholic kingdom. In this battle, social agents like the state, church, political elites and society were constituent parts of the emergence and regulation of an increasingly complex and diversified religious arena. In the process, a diversified social matrix - ie, a religious otherness - contested Catholic homogenisation.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-02-07</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2010-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>5000</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>25338</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>United Kingdom</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>en_GB</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>Religion and Society</gtr:description><gtr:end>2009-09-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>Arts &amp; Humanities Research Council (AHRC)</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:fundingRef>AH/F007566/1</gtr:fundingRef><gtr:id>7B61A2EE-2D7B-40FA-8996-E248D875C718</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>54468ea3390ae9.84718134</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Public</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2007-10-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput></gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>I myself have continued to work a lot in the area of religious regulation and secularism, which were the subjects which led Ludue&amp;nt